00:05:02.809 --> 00:05:05.100
So I don't know how much--
this is kind of last minute,

00:05:05.100 --> 00:05:06.140
so I don't know how
much you've already

00:05:06.140 --> 00:05:07.223
seen about sea level rise.

00:05:07.223 --> 00:05:11.080
But I want to talk a little
bit about the process.

00:05:11.080 --> 00:05:12.600
There's a lot of
different factors

00:05:12.600 --> 00:05:13.766
that go into sea level rise.

00:05:13.766 --> 00:05:16.240
Of course, as the water
warms, it expands.

00:05:16.240 --> 00:05:17.780
So that's called
thermal expansion.

00:05:17.780 --> 00:05:21.820
Also, you have melting of ice,
of glaciers, and ice sheets,

00:05:21.820 --> 00:05:23.510
adding volume to the water.

00:05:23.510 --> 00:05:25.870
You have vertical land movement.

00:05:25.870 --> 00:05:28.870
So sometimes, in some places,
the land is subsiding.

00:05:28.870 --> 00:05:32.160
Some places, it's uplifting--
compaction, other things,

00:05:32.160 --> 00:05:35.980
all these add to sea level
rise as we experience it

00:05:35.980 --> 00:05:37.180
at any location.

00:05:37.180 --> 00:05:39.200
Over the 20th century,
thermal expansion

00:05:39.200 --> 00:05:41.040
was really the driving factor.

00:05:41.040 --> 00:05:43.690
But in the 21st century,
as we move further

00:05:43.690 --> 00:05:45.800
into the 21st
century, what really

00:05:45.800 --> 00:05:48.780
is striking is the
potential for ice melt

00:05:48.780 --> 00:05:53.029
and the melting of the glaciers
to really add and accelerate

00:05:53.029 --> 00:05:54.320
the sea level rise that we see.

00:05:54.320 --> 00:05:57.650
So in the ice sheets,
there's a potential of tens

00:05:57.650 --> 00:05:59.827
of meters of sea level
rise, were they to all--

00:05:59.827 --> 00:06:01.410
and now, they're not
going to all melt

00:06:01.410 --> 00:06:02.560
in the next few centuries.

00:06:02.560 --> 00:06:04.556
But there's a big potential.

00:06:04.556 --> 00:06:06.180
And that's one of
the big uncertainties

00:06:06.180 --> 00:06:09.050
in being able to project
sea level rise, especially

00:06:09.050 --> 00:06:13.780
out into the later part of
the 21st century-- just how

00:06:13.780 --> 00:06:15.920
much of that ice
is going to melt?

00:06:15.920 --> 00:06:19.690
So the other thing, that
I know Kerry talked about

00:06:19.690 --> 00:06:22.600
earlier this week, was
that sea level rise is not

00:06:22.600 --> 00:06:25.400
experienced in the same
way in every location.

00:06:25.400 --> 00:06:28.140
So here in Boston, we're
not going to see just

00:06:28.140 --> 00:06:29.520
global mean sea level rise.

00:06:29.520 --> 00:06:31.440
GMSLR is just Global Mean.

00:06:31.440 --> 00:06:34.160
That's just the average sea
level rise around the planet.

00:06:34.160 --> 00:06:36.570
We're going to experience a
different rate of sea level

00:06:36.570 --> 00:06:38.584
rise because of this
vertical land movement.

00:06:38.584 --> 00:06:40.292
Here in Boston, we're
actually subsiding.

00:06:43.200 --> 00:06:45.940
And part of the
vertical land movement

00:06:45.940 --> 00:06:48.000
is in response to
glaciers that were

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:50.390
like 12 to 20,000
years ago-- the land

00:06:50.390 --> 00:06:52.060
is still adjusting to that.

00:06:52.060 --> 00:06:54.190
We also have changes in
ocean dynamics, which

00:06:54.190 --> 00:06:55.540
I'll talk about in a minute.

00:06:55.540 --> 00:06:57.450
And we have something
that's called ice sheet

00:06:57.450 --> 00:06:58.810
fingerprints, which
I think you've had

00:06:58.810 --> 00:07:00.000
a little bit of exposure to.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:01.958
But that is one of the
coolest things I learned

00:07:01.958 --> 00:07:03.440
as being a part of this BRAG.

00:07:03.440 --> 00:07:04.940
So I thought it was
very interesting

00:07:04.940 --> 00:07:06.439
and I wanted to
share that with you.

00:07:06.439 --> 00:07:10.380
So the ocean dynamics is-- as
you know, I'm a hydrologist.

00:07:10.380 --> 00:07:11.480
So I deal with freshwater.

00:07:11.480 --> 00:07:15.390
So I didn't have any real formal
training in ocean dynamics.

00:07:15.390 --> 00:07:18.010
And I found out that
the surface of the ocean

00:07:18.010 --> 00:07:19.490
is actually very bumpy.

00:07:19.490 --> 00:07:22.120
Because of currents, it's
not flat like you'd think.

00:07:22.120 --> 00:07:25.740
And so as those currents make
their way around the globe,

00:07:25.740 --> 00:07:29.020
the different elevations
of the water surface

00:07:29.020 --> 00:07:30.280
are very different.

00:07:30.280 --> 00:07:33.630
And as those elevation
as those currents change,

00:07:33.630 --> 00:07:36.540
it changes-- it affects the
elevation of the water surface.

00:07:36.540 --> 00:07:39.262
So as warming occurs,
sometimes we're

00:07:39.262 --> 00:07:40.720
expecting that some
of the currents

00:07:40.720 --> 00:07:43.650
may slow down, which may
cause a relaxing of the water

00:07:43.650 --> 00:07:48.990
surface at the current and shift
the water at the shoreline.

00:07:48.990 --> 00:07:53.870
There's also changes due to more
or less saltiness in the ocean

00:07:53.870 --> 00:07:55.210
and warmth.

00:07:55.210 --> 00:07:59.880
And then we have
these big climate--

00:07:59.880 --> 00:08:02.460
what they call teleconnections--
where these big climate

00:08:02.460 --> 00:08:05.070
events-- one, in
particular, in the Atlantic

00:08:05.070 --> 00:08:08.240
is called the North
Atlantic Oscillation, which

00:08:08.240 --> 00:08:14.200
effects where currents go and
also affects the sea levels as

00:08:14.200 --> 00:08:14.700
well.

00:08:14.700 --> 00:08:18.550
So these ocean dynamics
could impact sea level rise

00:08:18.550 --> 00:08:23.150
along the New England coast as
much as 10 centimeters by 2100.

00:08:23.150 --> 00:08:25.250
So there's all these
factors besides just

00:08:25.250 --> 00:08:29.110
the thermal expansion
that add to the sea level

00:08:29.110 --> 00:08:31.590
rise we may see.

00:08:31.590 --> 00:08:34.659
This idea of ice fingerprints
is pretty amazing.

00:08:34.659 --> 00:08:37.169
So as ice sheets
melt, they add water.

00:08:37.169 --> 00:08:38.089
That's obvious.

00:08:38.089 --> 00:08:39.630
But one thing that
I didn't realize--

00:08:39.630 --> 00:08:42.250
I never quite understood until
I was a part of this BRAG--

00:08:42.250 --> 00:08:44.810
is that the ice sheets
are so massive that they

00:08:44.810 --> 00:08:45.980
have a gravitational pull.

00:08:45.980 --> 00:08:48.300
And they actually pull
the water up to them.

00:08:48.300 --> 00:08:51.240
And as they melt, then
that mass reduces,

00:08:51.240 --> 00:08:53.120
and so the gravitational
pull reduces.

00:08:53.120 --> 00:08:56.270
So when you're close to an
ice sheet that's melting,

00:08:56.270 --> 00:08:57.960
the water level--
even though water

00:08:57.960 --> 00:09:00.010
is being added to the
ocean at that point,

00:09:00.010 --> 00:09:04.660
the water levels are actually
depressing, going down.

00:09:04.660 --> 00:09:07.560
That means it's distributing
farther out into the ocean.

00:09:07.560 --> 00:09:09.610
So when you're far
away from an ice sheet,

00:09:09.610 --> 00:09:12.200
the water level's actually going
up because of that ice sheet

00:09:12.200 --> 00:09:12.700
melting.

00:09:12.700 --> 00:09:14.680
And so they can model--
they've gotten better

00:09:14.680 --> 00:09:18.880
at modeling and predicting
these kinds of impacts.

00:09:18.880 --> 00:09:22.030
So this line, here,
is how the ocean

00:09:22.030 --> 00:09:25.170
would look if it was just a
flat surface around the sphere.

00:09:25.170 --> 00:09:27.780
But this line here
shows that impact

00:09:27.780 --> 00:09:29.820
where the massive
ice sheet is pulling

00:09:29.820 --> 00:09:31.800
the water up next to it.

00:09:31.800 --> 00:09:35.840
And then as the ice sheet
melts, this water level

00:09:35.840 --> 00:09:38.940
actually drops here and
goes up farther out.

00:09:38.940 --> 00:09:40.880
So we're going to be--
because we're very far

00:09:40.880 --> 00:09:44.150
from the Antarctic
ice sheets, we're

00:09:44.150 --> 00:09:47.580
actually going to be seeing
more than global mean sea level

00:09:47.580 --> 00:09:51.790
rise because of this relaxing
of the gravitational pull

00:09:51.790 --> 00:09:52.920
from the ice sheets.

00:09:52.920 --> 00:09:54.794
Which I just think that's
really fascinating.

00:09:54.794 --> 00:09:56.450
I would have never thought that.

00:09:56.450 --> 00:09:59.550
So because we're close to
Greenland, as Greenland melts,

00:09:59.550 --> 00:10:02.990
we're actually going to see
a reduction in sea level rise

00:10:02.990 --> 00:10:04.480
because we're
close to Greenland.

00:10:04.480 --> 00:10:07.710
But Greenland is pretty small
relative to the Antarctic.

00:10:07.710 --> 00:10:10.930
So as the Antarctic
melts, or if it collapses,

00:10:10.930 --> 00:10:13.660
we're actually going
to see as much as 20%

00:10:13.660 --> 00:10:17.730
or more increase over
global mean sea level rise

00:10:17.730 --> 00:10:23.970
because of that impact of that
mass redistribution of water.

00:10:23.970 --> 00:10:25.740
And so all those
things were taken--

00:10:25.740 --> 00:10:29.670
the BRAG looked into all
those different factors.

00:10:29.670 --> 00:10:33.940
And actually, Rob DeConto,
who works at UMass-Amherst,

00:10:33.940 --> 00:10:38.680
has a method for incorporating
all that into a model that

00:10:38.680 --> 00:10:40.810
can then project levels
of sea level rise,

00:10:40.810 --> 00:10:42.920
specifically for Boston here.

00:10:42.920 --> 00:10:48.150
So out of the BRAG came
some specific predictions

00:10:48.150 --> 00:10:51.676
of sea level arise under the
different emissions scenarios.

00:10:51.676 --> 00:10:54.050
You probably learned something
about emissions scenarios.

00:10:54.050 --> 00:10:57.320
If we have low carbon
emissions, because we

00:10:57.320 --> 00:11:02.070
go to renewable energy
sources, or if we continue

00:11:02.070 --> 00:11:04.370
on with the high
burning of fossil fuels,

00:11:04.370 --> 00:11:06.280
we have high emissions scenario.

00:11:06.280 --> 00:11:09.290
So here is the high emissions
scenario sea level rise.

00:11:09.290 --> 00:11:11.350
So it could be as
high-- the mean

00:11:11.350 --> 00:11:13.740
around four to five
feet of sea level rise,

00:11:13.740 --> 00:11:16.470
could be as high as seven
feet of sea level rise

00:11:16.470 --> 00:11:17.950
by the end of the century.

00:11:17.950 --> 00:11:20.840
Whereas if we follow the
lower emissions scenarios-- so

00:11:20.840 --> 00:11:24.860
if we reduce our carbon
emissions in the atmosphere,

00:11:24.860 --> 00:11:26.870
we could then have
sea level rise

00:11:26.870 --> 00:11:28.380
that's more in
the realm of three

00:11:28.380 --> 00:11:30.130
to four feet, two to four feet.

00:11:30.130 --> 00:11:32.080
So what we do now--
what the take away

00:11:32.080 --> 00:11:34.880
from for many of the things
that came out of the BRAG was,

00:11:34.880 --> 00:11:36.710
what we do know makes
a big difference

00:11:36.710 --> 00:11:39.444
later in the semester.
(LAUGHING) Semester!

00:11:39.444 --> 00:11:41.250
You can tell-- later
in the semester

00:11:41.250 --> 00:11:42.560
and later in the century.

00:11:42.560 --> 00:11:43.060
Right?

