00:11:43.420 --> 00:11:44.420
- Quite a long semester.

00:11:44.420 --> 00:11:46.300
- Yeah, that's a very
long semester, right.

00:11:46.300 --> 00:11:48.040
Yeah, you probably
won't see the impact

00:11:48.040 --> 00:11:49.165
by the end of the semester.

00:11:49.165 --> 00:11:50.229
- The final exam--

00:11:50.229 --> 00:11:51.270
- Yeah, the final, right.

00:11:51.270 --> 00:11:54.040
There will be a test at
the end of this century.

00:11:54.040 --> 00:11:57.670
How did we do?
(LAUGHING) That's good.

00:11:57.670 --> 00:12:01.270
So that was one Initiative
that Boston generated

00:12:01.270 --> 00:12:04.230
to try to assess what
climate change means

00:12:04.230 --> 00:12:05.690
for Boston specifically.

00:12:05.690 --> 00:12:07.200
And they're just
finally releasing,

00:12:07.200 --> 00:12:09.530
I think it should come out
in the next month or so,

00:12:09.530 --> 00:12:11.590
the results of the
vulnerability assessment

00:12:11.590 --> 00:12:14.430
that used the
scientific consensus

00:12:14.430 --> 00:12:18.220
from the BRAG for
the four impacts,

00:12:18.220 --> 00:12:21.010
and then look at places in
the city that's vulnerable.

00:12:21.010 --> 00:12:22.760
Another project that
I was involved in

00:12:22.760 --> 00:12:25.490
was actually funded by the
Federal Highway Administration

00:12:25.490 --> 00:12:26.700
and Mass DOT.

00:12:26.700 --> 00:12:30.310
I'm an engineer, so I like
to deal with the stuff that's

00:12:30.310 --> 00:12:31.320
on the ground.

00:12:31.320 --> 00:12:34.210
So we worked, we were hired
by Mass DOT and the Federal

00:12:34.210 --> 00:12:37.380
Highway Administration, as part
of the climate change pilot

00:12:37.380 --> 00:12:40.100
project to look at the
impacts of sea level

00:12:40.100 --> 00:12:42.560
rise and coastal
storms on the Central

00:12:42.560 --> 00:12:45.190
Artery, what we affectionately
know as the Big Dig

00:12:45.190 --> 00:12:46.180
around here.

00:12:46.180 --> 00:12:47.650
So I'm going to tell you
just a little bit about that.

00:12:47.650 --> 00:12:49.816
Here's our project team,
and included several people

00:12:49.816 --> 00:12:51.200
from UMass-Boston.

00:12:51.200 --> 00:12:53.300
Our modeler was Kirk
Bosma from Woods Hole

00:12:53.300 --> 00:12:58.030
Group down in East Falmouth,
and Mass DOT personnel.

00:12:58.030 --> 00:12:59.820
So we all worked
together on this.

00:12:59.820 --> 00:13:03.810
And the main
objective was to see

00:13:03.810 --> 00:13:06.075
what was vulnerable in
the Central Atery project.

00:13:06.075 --> 00:13:08.700
And we're not just talking about
the tunnel but all the highway

00:13:08.700 --> 00:13:12.030
infrastructure and the tunnels
that were a part of it.

00:13:12.030 --> 00:13:14.950
And then how could
we-- what could we

00:13:14.950 --> 00:13:17.342
do to reduce those
vulnerabilities?

00:13:17.342 --> 00:13:19.300
So this is just an image
of the Central Artery.

00:13:19.300 --> 00:13:20.924
I'm sure that you're
all pretty-- well,

00:13:20.924 --> 00:13:22.080
maybe you're not.

00:13:22.080 --> 00:13:23.580
You're not, maybe,
from around here.

00:13:23.580 --> 00:13:24.830
So this is the Central Artery.

00:13:24.830 --> 00:13:27.880
Here's a picture of what it
looks like now, where the Rose

00:13:27.880 --> 00:13:29.170
Kennedy Greenway used to be.

00:13:29.170 --> 00:13:30.330
It was an elevated highway.

00:13:30.330 --> 00:13:34.180
Now it's a tunnel
under the city.

00:13:34.180 --> 00:13:37.810
And so you can imagine that
an agency like Mass DOT

00:13:37.810 --> 00:13:39.740
worries about things
like tunnel entrances.

00:13:39.740 --> 00:13:41.920
What happens if water goes
in the tunnel entrance?

00:13:41.920 --> 00:13:43.504
Or they have these
big vent buildings.

00:13:43.504 --> 00:13:45.878
So when you've got this tunnel,
you need to ventilate it.

00:13:45.878 --> 00:13:47.510
So they have these
big vent buildings.

00:13:47.510 --> 00:13:49.440
And they have vents
right at ground surface.

00:13:49.440 --> 00:13:51.800
So you have to worry
about what sea level rise

00:13:51.800 --> 00:13:54.950
or coastal flooding could
look like in these areas.

00:13:54.950 --> 00:13:56.270
And I've done a lot of work.

00:13:56.270 --> 00:13:57.780
I've been working on
this for over 10 years

00:13:57.780 --> 00:13:59.140
along with my other colleagues.

00:13:59.140 --> 00:14:02.210
And what we had
previously done was just

00:14:02.210 --> 00:14:03.570
what is called a bath tub mat.

00:14:03.570 --> 00:14:05.542
So you just take a flat
surface, and you cut it

00:14:05.542 --> 00:14:07.750
through the terrain, and
you say, anything below it's

00:14:07.750 --> 00:14:10.120
going to be flooded and
anything above it is not.

00:14:10.120 --> 00:14:12.360
Well that's fine when
that's, basically,

00:14:12.360 --> 00:14:14.310
all you have the
money or time to do.

00:14:14.310 --> 00:14:16.300
But really, what
you need to do is

00:14:16.300 --> 00:14:20.050
develop a model that can
simulate waves, and wind,

00:14:20.050 --> 00:14:21.790
and ocean current
so that you know.

00:14:21.790 --> 00:14:24.970
Because this map
shows a flat surface

00:14:24.970 --> 00:14:29.440
at 12 feet where flooding
would be in Boston.

00:14:29.440 --> 00:14:33.170
But this actually shows
how a hyrdodynamic model

00:14:33.170 --> 00:14:35.710
would simulate the
same kind of an event.

00:14:35.710 --> 00:14:39.110
And so you can see the red
means higher than 12 feet.

00:14:39.110 --> 00:14:42.830
So along-- this is actually
a simulation of a nor'easter.

00:14:42.830 --> 00:14:45.360
One of the reasons that
nor'easters impacts us

00:14:45.360 --> 00:14:47.560
in Boston is because
Boston Harbor is open--

00:14:47.560 --> 00:14:49.230
opens right up to the Northeast.

00:14:49.230 --> 00:14:52.680
So people along the South coast,
here in Quincy in those areas,

00:14:52.680 --> 00:14:56.620
are going to get higher
impacts because of waves,

00:14:56.620 --> 00:15:00.220
and because the water is
push-- because of storm surge--

00:15:00.220 --> 00:15:02.150
than they are in
the Northern coast.

00:15:02.150 --> 00:15:05.670
So that's why we decided that we
would-- because we had funding

00:15:05.670 --> 00:15:08.020
from the Federal
Highway Administration

00:15:08.020 --> 00:15:11.690
and from Mass DOT, we built
this big, fancy-shmancy model

00:15:11.690 --> 00:15:15.930
that actually includes
much of the Atlantic

00:15:15.930 --> 00:15:19.500
so we could bring in nor'easter
storms and hurricanes

00:15:19.500 --> 00:15:22.160
to assess what those would
look-- what flooding would

00:15:22.160 --> 00:15:25.180
look like from those events.

00:15:25.180 --> 00:15:29.340
And we also, because Mass DOT
was interested in understanding

00:15:29.340 --> 00:15:32.942
the vulnerability of
individual structures-- so

00:15:32.942 --> 00:15:34.650
the vent buildings,
the tunnel entrances,

00:15:34.650 --> 00:15:38.010
things like that-- we had a
very fine-resolution grid.

00:15:38.010 --> 00:15:40.520
So all of these little
dots-- the model

00:15:40.520 --> 00:15:42.910
had a prediction
for all those dots.

00:15:42.910 --> 00:15:46.250
So this ended up being a
very large numerical model

00:15:46.250 --> 00:15:46.976
that was built.

00:15:46.976 --> 00:15:48.600
But it really was
the next step that we

00:15:48.600 --> 00:15:52.810
needed to take beyond
the bathtub maps.

00:15:52.810 --> 00:15:56.570
We incorporated sea level
rise, we picked points off

00:15:56.570 --> 00:16:00.320
of the highest
emissions scenario

00:16:00.320 --> 00:16:03.710
to look at what coastal
flooding would look like now,

00:16:03.710 --> 00:16:07.740
in 2030, and 2070,
and ultimately 2100.

00:16:07.740 --> 00:16:10.330
And the outcome
of this-- so this

00:16:10.330 --> 00:16:11.920
was like a two year project.

00:16:11.920 --> 00:16:17.340
And the outcome of this
model was the probability

00:16:17.340 --> 00:16:19.210
of flooding at
different locations

00:16:19.210 --> 00:16:22.060
throughout Massachusetts--
throughout Boston.

00:16:22.060 --> 00:16:26.210
So it was funded by Mass DOT--
they were most interested

00:16:26.210 --> 00:16:28.600
in the Mass DOT structures.

00:16:28.600 --> 00:16:30.700
But it also gave
us a map where you

00:16:30.700 --> 00:16:32.920
could-- where other people,
other communities all

00:16:32.920 --> 00:16:35.860
along the coastline could look
at the results of this model

00:16:35.860 --> 00:16:38.540
and say, what does that mean
for flooding for us as well?

00:16:38.540 --> 00:16:43.920
So this is an image of, as
you can see, the Boston area.

00:16:43.920 --> 00:16:45.690
The little-- the
green here-- so this,

00:16:45.690 --> 00:16:49.070
right now, is the
probability of flooding.

00:16:49.070 --> 00:16:52.900
So the greenish color
is around 1% chance.

00:16:52.900 --> 00:16:55.590
So if any of you ever heard
the term, The 100 Year Flood

00:16:55.590 --> 00:16:58.140
or the 1% Chance
Flood, that's the one

00:16:58.140 --> 00:17:00.130
that FEMA worries about a lot.

00:17:00.130 --> 00:17:03.910
So we were able to
actually predict

00:17:03.910 --> 00:17:06.109
what the probabilities
of flooding were.

00:17:06.109 --> 00:17:08.900
And this is the
Greenway in East Boston.

00:17:08.900 --> 00:17:11.550
Here, we have South Boston.

00:17:11.550 --> 00:17:15.411
Here, we have down where
I am on Columbia Point,

00:17:15.411 --> 00:17:16.369
up here in Charlestown.

00:17:16.369 --> 00:17:17.760
So this is current conditions.

00:17:17.760 --> 00:17:21.470
So there is some probability
of flooding in parts of Boston

00:17:21.470 --> 00:17:23.579
under current conditions.

00:17:23.579 --> 00:17:27.079
But the probabilities
are low-- 1% or less.

00:17:27.079 --> 00:17:30.451
But when we get to 2030,
you see the colors change.

00:17:30.451 --> 00:17:32.700
Not only do the colors change,
but the extent changes.

00:17:32.700 --> 00:17:36.280
So now the probability is
more in the area of 2% to 5%.

00:17:36.280 --> 00:17:38.630
So now we're starting
to see, rather than once

00:17:38.630 --> 00:17:40.030
every 100 years
on average, we're

00:17:40.030 --> 00:17:43.610
seeing once every 50 years
or more-- probability

00:17:43.610 --> 00:17:47.120
of flooding-- and also seeing
much greater extent of flooding

00:17:47.120 --> 00:17:48.430
in these areas as well.

00:17:48.430 --> 00:17:50.220
And then we get the 2070.

00:17:50.220 --> 00:17:52.290
And then we start seeing
a lot of flooding.

00:17:52.290 --> 00:17:54.670
And in particular, we
see a lot of flooding

00:17:54.670 --> 00:17:58.610
in here, in Cambridge
and Back Bay

00:17:58.610 --> 00:18:00.910
because-- so what
we're doing here

00:18:00.910 --> 00:18:04.090
is we're modeling sea level
rise plus the addition of storms

00:18:04.090 --> 00:18:05.150
coming in on top of that.

00:18:05.150 --> 00:18:08.870
So a storm surge--
so by 2050 to 2060,

00:18:08.870 --> 00:18:10.740
somewhere around
in there, if you

00:18:10.740 --> 00:18:14.110
get an event-- a storm
surge on top of a high tide,

00:18:14.110 --> 00:18:16.460
it can actually get
around the Charles River

00:18:16.460 --> 00:18:18.410
dam and the Amelia Earhart dam.

00:18:18.410 --> 00:18:21.095
And then you begin to have
flooding in these areas that

00:18:21.095 --> 00:18:22.970
weren't used to being
flooded, because that's

00:18:22.970 --> 00:18:24.136
why the dams were put there.

00:18:24.136 --> 00:18:27.520
So we have flooding in
Cambridge and those areas,

00:18:27.520 --> 00:18:30.710
a lot of flooding up in
Charleston and Somerville,

00:18:30.710 --> 00:18:34.310
and of course, South Boston,
South End, and all these areas.

00:18:34.310 --> 00:18:40.220
So this gave Mass DOT a chance
to figure out what is the risk.

00:18:40.220 --> 00:18:42.290
What's the probability
of getting flooding?

00:18:42.290 --> 00:18:44.940
And we could also take a
particular probability--

00:18:44.940 --> 00:18:48.480
a 1% flood probability-- and
see what the depths would be.

00:18:48.480 --> 00:18:52.990
So here, we're looking at
the same sort of scale.

00:18:52.990 --> 00:18:56.110
The Greenway in East Boston,
under current conditions,

00:18:56.110 --> 00:18:57.150
has a potential.

00:18:57.150 --> 00:18:59.549
If it's a 1% event,
if that occurs,

00:18:59.549 --> 00:19:01.590
the depths are going to
be around a half a foot--

00:19:01.590 --> 00:19:04.430
a half a foot to a
foot-- so not anything,

00:19:04.430 --> 00:19:06.880
probably, terribly disruptive.

00:19:06.880 --> 00:19:11.040
But if you get into 2030,
then you get an extension,

00:19:11.040 --> 00:19:13.590
then the flooding depths
get more extensive,

00:19:13.590 --> 00:19:14.510
and they get deeper.

00:19:14.510 --> 00:19:16.970
And again, as you
can imagine, by 2070,

00:19:16.970 --> 00:19:18.470
not only do you
have a higher chance

00:19:18.470 --> 00:19:22.280
of flooding in more areas,
but you also have more depths.

00:19:22.280 --> 00:19:25.210
So this gave Mass
DOT-- and anybody else,

00:19:25.210 --> 00:19:28.770
basically, in Boston that's
interested in the impacts

00:19:28.770 --> 00:19:31.300
of coastal flooding, which is
the combination of sea level

00:19:31.300 --> 00:19:35.980
rise and coastal storms-- some
information to how to plan,

00:19:35.980 --> 00:19:38.120
how to think about what
sea level rise could mean.

00:19:38.120 --> 00:19:39.630
And of course, we can zoom in.

00:19:39.630 --> 00:19:43.010
Mass DOT and others can look
at individual infrastructures.

00:19:43.010 --> 00:19:46.260
I showed this map to
a bunch of CEOs that

00:19:46.260 --> 00:19:47.680
had property in South Boston.

00:19:47.680 --> 00:19:50.510
And there was literally
a verbal gasp in the air

00:19:50.510 --> 00:19:55.000
because the blues are around
30% to 50% probability, by 2070,

00:19:55.000 --> 00:19:56.270
of flooding.

00:19:56.270 --> 00:19:58.490
So that's a really
high probability

00:19:58.490 --> 00:20:01.140
of flooding occurring
in these areas.

00:20:01.140 --> 00:20:04.210
So then you can start
looking at what are we

00:20:04.210 --> 00:20:05.590
going to do about it.

00:20:05.590 --> 00:20:08.600
So other things that come out
of this model are the timing.

00:20:08.600 --> 00:20:11.140
So the water comes in, we
know what the depths is,

00:20:11.140 --> 00:20:12.330
how long does it last?

00:20:12.330 --> 00:20:16.130
So how deep it gets, how
long the flooding lasts.

00:20:16.130 --> 00:20:17.630
Then you can start
figuring out what

00:20:17.630 --> 00:20:18.410
we're going to do about it.

00:20:18.410 --> 00:20:20.451
So you could do something
as simple as putting up

00:20:20.451 --> 00:20:21.630
flood-proof doors.

00:20:21.630 --> 00:20:24.847
We found out in the Big Dig,
there are a lot of doors.

00:20:24.847 --> 00:20:26.430
There are an enormous
amount of doors.

00:20:26.430 --> 00:20:29.160
So as they replace
doors over time,

00:20:29.160 --> 00:20:31.050
they replace them with
flood-proof doors.

00:20:31.050 --> 00:20:33.570
So that's a fairly easy fix.

00:20:33.570 --> 00:20:36.170
There's also, in areas that
are going to be flooded,

00:20:36.170 --> 00:20:38.640
but it's going to be
either less than two feet,

00:20:38.640 --> 00:20:41.370
or it's going to occur
over a very short time,

00:20:41.370 --> 00:20:44.190
you could put up these
things called temporary flood

00:20:44.190 --> 00:20:44.950
barriers.

00:20:44.950 --> 00:20:47.790
Aquafence is a builder of
these temporary flood barriers.

00:20:47.790 --> 00:20:50.800
And Massport actually
has bought a system

00:20:50.800 --> 00:20:52.250
of these temporary
flood barriers.

00:20:52.250 --> 00:20:57.590
And this shows a picture of
them doing an emergency-- see

00:20:57.590 --> 00:20:58.440
how long it took.

00:20:58.440 --> 00:21:01.240
And it took them like,
I think, 45 minutes

00:21:01.240 --> 00:21:03.319
to put up the temporary
barriers around

00:21:03.319 --> 00:21:04.360
this particular building.

00:21:04.360 --> 00:21:05.950
So they went and did a drill.

00:21:05.950 --> 00:21:09.430
So there are ways that
you can protect yourself

00:21:09.430 --> 00:21:11.650
that aren't terribly
expensive and can

00:21:11.650 --> 00:21:13.357
be put away in the warehouse.

00:21:13.357 --> 00:21:14.940
And then when you--
the good thing is,

00:21:14.940 --> 00:21:17.170
we have three to
five-day lead times

00:21:17.170 --> 00:21:19.440
now, for big storms
that are coming in.

00:21:19.440 --> 00:21:21.170
So you have time to prepare.

00:21:21.170 --> 00:21:25.960
So this gave Mass DOT
a chance to really

00:21:25.960 --> 00:21:28.030
know what sea level rise
and coastal flooding

00:21:28.030 --> 00:21:32.404
would mean for their
particular infrastructure,

00:21:32.404 --> 00:21:33.570
and then to be able to plan.

00:21:33.570 --> 00:21:35.640
So the good news, for
them and for Boston,

00:21:35.640 --> 00:21:38.720
is that over the short term,
currently, there is exposure.

00:21:38.720 --> 00:21:40.100
There is risk of flooding.

00:21:40.100 --> 00:21:41.650
And we kind of all
knew that, right?

00:21:41.650 --> 00:21:43.382
Now we just know what
the probability is.

00:21:43.382 --> 00:21:45.090
So it's fairly low
probability right now.

00:21:45.090 --> 00:21:47.011
So we have time
to figure out how

00:21:47.011 --> 00:21:48.260
we're going to deal with this.

00:21:48.260 --> 00:21:52.230
But by the time you
get to 2030, you

00:21:52.230 --> 00:21:54.980
have to start worrying about
more substantial flooding

00:21:54.980 --> 00:21:58.150
and incorporating
this flood-proofing

00:21:58.150 --> 00:22:01.520
and accommodation
into the maintenance

00:22:01.520 --> 00:22:04.490
of these particular buildings.

00:22:04.490 --> 00:22:06.870
The bad news is there
were some-- even

00:22:06.870 --> 00:22:10.040
under current conditions,
there are some tunnel openings

00:22:10.040 --> 00:22:11.200
that are vulnerable.

00:22:11.200 --> 00:22:12.190
So you have to think
about what we would

00:22:12.190 --> 00:22:13.560
do if a storm did come in.

00:22:13.560 --> 00:22:17.590
And those vulnerable tunnel
openings do increase over time.

00:22:17.590 --> 00:22:21.884
So Mass DOT is doing a lot
of ground truthing right now,

00:22:21.884 --> 00:22:23.800
making sure that the
stuff that the model said

00:22:23.800 --> 00:22:25.070
is actually true.

00:22:25.070 --> 00:22:28.770
And then they're also developing
a plan over the long term

00:22:28.770 --> 00:22:31.580
with how they're going to
incorporate this information.

00:22:31.580 --> 00:22:33.810
Just one more quick
thing about other things

00:22:33.810 --> 00:22:36.340
that we've been doing
related to sea level

00:22:36.340 --> 00:22:38.580
rise in the Boston area.

00:22:38.580 --> 00:22:41.760
My colleague, Paul
Kirshen and I have

00:22:41.760 --> 00:22:45.020
been working for about the last
eight years in East Boston.

00:22:45.020 --> 00:22:47.370
We had a research
project that was

00:22:47.370 --> 00:22:50.820
funded by NOAA, the National
Oceanographic and Atmospheric

00:22:50.820 --> 00:22:54.400
Administration who was
interested in knowing

00:22:54.400 --> 00:22:56.310
what sea level rise
and coastal flooding

00:22:56.310 --> 00:22:58.790
means for environmental
justice communities.

00:22:58.790 --> 00:23:02.540
And so we picked East
Boston as a focus area.

00:23:02.540 --> 00:23:05.970
And the first thing we did was
we had two research projects.

00:23:05.970 --> 00:23:07.700
So this is research in action.

00:23:07.700 --> 00:23:11.790
We had two sequential
research projects

00:23:11.790 --> 00:23:14.464
where we went in and met
with East Boston residents,

00:23:14.464 --> 00:23:16.380
found out what they knew
about climate change.

00:23:16.380 --> 00:23:20.720
We gave them some ideas of what
we knew about climate change,

00:23:20.720 --> 00:23:23.530
and then surveyed the
residents to find out--

00:23:23.530 --> 00:23:25.850
and told them about what are
the options-- how can you

00:23:25.850 --> 00:23:28.960
protect yourself, how can
the city protect itself

00:23:28.960 --> 00:23:33.050
from these flooding events--
and then got feedback

00:23:33.050 --> 00:23:38.700
from the individual residents
as to what they felt would work

00:23:38.700 --> 00:23:40.250
and wouldn't work.

00:23:40.250 --> 00:23:44.650
And out of that, then,
came a series of workshops

00:23:44.650 --> 00:23:49.860
where we brought together
people from Boston agencies--

00:23:49.860 --> 00:23:54.360
Massport, Mass
DOT, National Grid,

00:23:54.360 --> 00:23:56.460
the City of Boston,
all kinds of agencies

00:23:56.460 --> 00:23:59.140
that were going to be
doing individual adaptation

00:23:59.140 --> 00:24:02.280
strategies in East Boston--
brought them together

00:24:02.280 --> 00:24:04.390
with the residents
of East Boston,

00:24:04.390 --> 00:24:07.570
had some workshops where
people shared their values

00:24:07.570 --> 00:24:08.900
and their priorities.

00:24:08.900 --> 00:24:12.520
The whole purpose was--
the hypothesis here

00:24:12.520 --> 00:24:15.690
was that, if you develop
a plan, rather than having

00:24:15.690 --> 00:24:18.020
all the individual
agencies develop

00:24:18.020 --> 00:24:20.340
their own plans for
their own infrastructure,

00:24:20.340 --> 00:24:24.730
if we got together and came
up with a plan that shared

00:24:24.730 --> 00:24:28.250
the plan across agencies
and across stakeholders,

00:24:28.250 --> 00:24:30.030
we could not only
meet the requirements

00:24:30.030 --> 00:24:31.670
of the individual
agencies, but also

00:24:31.670 --> 00:24:34.480
have a lot of co-benefits
for the residents

00:24:34.480 --> 00:24:37.630
and other people
involved in the area.

00:24:37.630 --> 00:24:40.860
So we brought together--
and this was mostly

00:24:40.860 --> 00:24:43.270
led by Paul Kirshen--
the residents

00:24:43.270 --> 00:24:46.590
with the governmental and
infrastructure agencies, shared

00:24:46.590 --> 00:24:51.150
values and plans, and
then engineers came up

00:24:51.150 --> 00:24:53.690
with a conceptual
flood-proofing, flood

00:24:53.690 --> 00:24:56.280
protection plan for East Boston.

00:24:56.280 --> 00:24:58.790
So people just got together,
rolled out these maps,

00:24:58.790 --> 00:25:00.640
and said, OK, what's important?

00:25:00.640 --> 00:25:02.660
People listened to
different stakeholders

00:25:02.660 --> 00:25:04.830
giving presentations,
and sat down,

00:25:04.830 --> 00:25:07.710
and hashed out what was
important, and ultimately came

00:25:07.710 --> 00:25:10.470
up with a map of
important features,

00:25:10.470 --> 00:25:13.420
within East Boston, that
needed to be protected,

00:25:13.420 --> 00:25:16.770
that were valued by
both the residents

00:25:16.770 --> 00:25:19.220
and the government
agencies and infrastructure

00:25:19.220 --> 00:25:20.650
agencies that were involved.

00:25:20.650 --> 00:25:24.260
And ultimately, out of
this came a conceptual plan

00:25:24.260 --> 00:25:29.180
that included a flood wall, that
included some landscape berms,

00:25:29.180 --> 00:25:31.730
and some beach nourishment,
and things like that.

00:25:31.730 --> 00:25:35.830
And the great thing about
this is, since the NOAA--

00:25:35.830 --> 00:25:41.040
the NOAA funded research that
we did lasted for six years.

00:25:41.040 --> 00:25:45.650
And then Paul and
NOAH-- N-O-A-H,

00:25:45.650 --> 00:25:49.180
which is the neighborhood of
affordable housing community

00:25:49.180 --> 00:25:53.460
advocacy group in East Boston--
went and got a Kresge grant.

00:25:53.460 --> 00:25:58.230
Yeah, so we were funded by NOAA
and we were working with NOAH.

00:25:58.230 --> 00:26:05.330
It was hard-- N-O-A-A, N-O-A-H--
so, got a Kresge to actually

00:26:05.330 --> 00:26:09.250
develop a real adaptation
plan for the city of Boston.

00:26:09.250 --> 00:26:12.682
And then very recently, the
Coastal Zone Management--

00:26:12.682 --> 00:26:15.140
it's hard, that's kind of washed
out-- but the Coastal Zone

00:26:15.140 --> 00:26:19.330
Management has given
the city of Boston money

00:26:19.330 --> 00:26:25.110
to actually start designing
protection for East Boston.

00:26:25.110 --> 00:26:27.970
And that includes-- so one
of the things that came out

00:26:27.970 --> 00:26:30.270
of this model-- we have--
so you saw the flood

00:26:30.270 --> 00:26:35.250
maps from the model
that showed flooding,

00:26:35.250 --> 00:26:37.720
and the probabilities, and the
depths at different places.

00:26:37.720 --> 00:26:40.800
The other thing that the model
shows you is flood pathways.

00:26:40.800 --> 00:26:43.840
So there are places
along the coast that

00:26:43.840 --> 00:26:46.140
are an entryway, that if
you block that entryway,

00:26:46.140 --> 00:26:49.180
you can actually save a lot
of the flooding behind it.

00:26:49.180 --> 00:26:52.930
So what the Coastal Zone
Management-- Massachusetts

00:26:52.930 --> 00:26:55.100
Coastal Zone Management
has actually given money--

00:26:55.100 --> 00:26:59.080
a grant to the city of
Boston to develop designs

00:26:59.080 --> 00:27:02.270
for closing those gaps.

00:27:02.270 --> 00:27:04.670
So one of the gaps
was the flood pathway

00:27:04.670 --> 00:27:07.750
that leads to all that flooding
that happens in the East Boston

00:27:07.750 --> 00:27:08.590
Greenway.

00:27:08.590 --> 00:27:11.050
The other is a
flood pathway that

00:27:11.050 --> 00:27:14.320
leads to flooding that comes in
up by the Schrafft's building

00:27:14.320 --> 00:27:15.970
up in Sullivan square.

00:27:15.970 --> 00:27:17.850
And that leads,
ultimately, to water

00:27:17.850 --> 00:27:21.160
that gets behind the
Charles River dam.

00:27:21.160 --> 00:27:24.580
So you close these two
flood pathways and you

00:27:24.580 --> 00:27:25.830
save a lot of flooding.

00:27:25.830 --> 00:27:28.660
So you don't have to do all
of that individual home flood

00:27:28.660 --> 00:27:29.380
proofing.

00:27:29.380 --> 00:27:31.890
So I really like this East
Boston project because it

00:27:31.890 --> 00:27:35.730
started by talking with the
residents, and now has ended--

00:27:35.730 --> 00:27:39.300
is currently in design stage.

00:27:39.300 --> 00:27:42.480
So it was really a
great example of how

00:27:42.480 --> 00:27:44.370
you can work with a
whole bunch of people

00:27:44.370 --> 00:27:46.411
and come out with something
that's actually going

00:27:46.411 --> 00:27:48.470
to happen-- be on the ground.

00:27:48.470 --> 00:27:50.960
So I'm going to end there.

00:27:50.960 --> 00:27:54.640
My colleague, Paul
Kershen, started this work

00:27:54.640 --> 00:27:58.300
in East Boston
with a study called

00:27:58.300 --> 00:28:02.180
"Climate's Long-term
Impacts on Metro Boston."

00:28:02.180 --> 00:28:04.280
And one of the take
away messages from that

00:28:04.280 --> 00:28:06.480
was that, "The most
expensive option, when

00:28:06.480 --> 00:28:08.910
dealing with climate
change, is to do nothing."

00:28:08.910 --> 00:28:11.611
so that's what I wanted
to leave you with.

