00:33:32.860 --> 00:33:35.600
add another foot or two to those
when I'm looking at base flood

00:33:35.600 --> 00:33:37.090
elevations?

00:33:37.090 --> 00:33:38.850
- To the FEMA maps-- well, yeah.

00:33:38.850 --> 00:33:42.530
So FEMA is-- (LAUGHING) how
much you gonna pay me for this?

00:33:42.530 --> 00:33:45.530
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:45.530 --> 00:33:47.870
- Well the projects
we do, we expect

00:33:47.870 --> 00:33:49.320
them to last 30 or 40 years.

00:33:49.320 --> 00:33:51.320
And I don't want to go
into some building that's

00:33:51.320 --> 00:33:53.850
got four feet of water
in it based off the maps

00:33:53.850 --> 00:33:54.900
that we have now.

00:33:54.900 --> 00:33:58.225
Yeah, so the FEMA maps simply
look backwards in time.

00:33:58.225 --> 00:34:00.100
They don't incorporate
climate change at all.

00:34:00.100 --> 00:34:03.080
So FEMA maps are developed
using the historical data.

00:34:03.080 --> 00:34:04.520
And this is by law.

00:34:04.520 --> 00:34:05.880
I mean, FEMA has no choice.

00:34:05.880 --> 00:34:08.050
This is how Congress
designated that they

00:34:08.050 --> 00:34:10.252
would develop these flood
insurance rate maps.

00:34:10.252 --> 00:34:11.960
They look in the
history, they figure out

00:34:11.960 --> 00:34:13.626
what's the probability
of flooding given

00:34:13.626 --> 00:34:16.110
our historical
record-- 100 year,

00:34:16.110 --> 00:34:19.280
500 year-- so that's the
1% chance and the point .2%

00:34:19.280 --> 00:34:22.130
chance of flooding.

00:34:22.130 --> 00:34:24.760
What you add to that--
that's one of the reasons

00:34:24.760 --> 00:34:27.000
we did this big
model for Boston,

00:34:27.000 --> 00:34:29.290
because we added sea
level rise into Boston

00:34:29.290 --> 00:34:32.760
and allowed the model to
simulate storm surge, and wave

00:34:32.760 --> 00:34:34.190
actions, and things like that.

00:34:34.190 --> 00:34:37.050
Because there are a lot of
other things besides sea level

00:34:37.050 --> 00:34:41.409
that's going to
impact the coastline.

00:34:41.409 --> 00:34:43.710
And so what you add
to the FEMA maps,

00:34:43.710 --> 00:34:48.489
if you're going to do that,
all depends on how vulnerable--

00:34:48.489 --> 00:34:49.929
how much risk you can take.

00:34:49.929 --> 00:34:53.540
So if you have a system--
if you have a building that,

00:34:53.540 --> 00:34:55.610
if it gets flooded,
oh well, it's messy.

00:34:55.610 --> 00:35:00.700
But you just clean it out
and you put stuff back,

00:35:00.700 --> 00:35:04.800
then you could probably handle a
5% or a 10% chance of flooding.

00:35:04.800 --> 00:35:07.649
But if you have something
like the Big Dig,

00:35:07.649 --> 00:35:10.190
where people drive through it,
and you don't want to fill up,

00:35:10.190 --> 00:35:12.270
then that has a very low risk.

00:35:12.270 --> 00:35:15.170
I mean, you could only handle
a very low risk of flooding.

00:35:15.170 --> 00:35:17.732
