00:36:09.930 --> 00:36:10.595
that might be?

00:36:10.595 --> 00:36:11.110
Thank you.

00:36:11.110 --> 00:36:12.650
- Yeah, that's a
really good question.

00:36:12.650 --> 00:36:14.800
So I have been-- it's
interesting, I'm a hydrologist

00:36:14.800 --> 00:36:16.820
and I got involved in sea level
rise for the last 10 years,

00:36:16.820 --> 00:36:19.403
and I'm finally getting to the
point where I can start looking

00:36:19.403 --> 00:36:20.860
at freshwater impacts again.

00:36:20.860 --> 00:36:24.630
So in Boston and in
many coastal cities,

00:36:24.630 --> 00:36:27.062
we have those that duel impact.

00:36:27.062 --> 00:36:28.770
We have the ocean
coming in from one side

00:36:28.770 --> 00:36:31.000
and we have rivers
with flood waters

00:36:31.000 --> 00:36:32.250
coming in from the other side.

00:36:32.250 --> 00:36:34.070
And we also have
storm drains, right?

00:36:34.070 --> 00:36:36.880
Where do the storm drains end?

00:36:36.880 --> 00:36:38.490
In the ocean, usually.

00:36:38.490 --> 00:36:40.630
And when they were built,
it was above high tide.

00:36:40.630 --> 00:36:42.550
Well when the high
tide rises to the point

00:36:42.550 --> 00:36:45.350
where it plugs up the end,
then that storm water that

00:36:45.350 --> 00:36:47.720
comes in-- usually when
we have a storm come in,

00:36:47.720 --> 00:36:50.240
and we get a storm
surge, and so it goes

00:36:50.240 --> 00:36:52.750
above the elevation of the
outlet of the storm drain,

00:36:52.750 --> 00:36:54.932
and so water can't flow
out there anymore--

00:36:54.932 --> 00:36:57.140
we also have a lot of
precipitation falling and a lot

00:36:57.140 --> 00:37:00.070
of storm water that's trying
to get out of that drain

00:37:00.070 --> 00:37:04.990
and can't because it's being
blocked by the storm tide.

00:37:04.990 --> 00:37:07.900
And so what happens is
the water just backs up.

00:37:07.900 --> 00:37:12.890
So the combination of freshwater
flooding and ocean flooding

00:37:12.890 --> 00:37:15.750
is going to be that,
upstream, there's

00:37:15.750 --> 00:37:17.560
going to be a lot
more flooding upstream

00:37:17.560 --> 00:37:21.530
and upriver because the water
just can't get out the way

00:37:21.530 --> 00:37:22.580
that it would normally.

00:37:22.580 --> 00:37:25.930
Now in the Charles-- we
have the Charles River dam

00:37:25.930 --> 00:37:32.690
that was actually developed,
designed with 6 massive pumps

00:37:32.690 --> 00:37:35.840
that were designed to pump the
largest flood that was ever

00:37:35.840 --> 00:37:37.261
recorded on the Charles.

00:37:37.261 --> 00:37:38.760
So the Charles River
dam is actually

00:37:38.760 --> 00:37:43.040
going to be OK for a
while, up until 2060, 2065.

00:37:43.040 --> 00:37:45.580
It's going to be able
to maintain that level.

00:37:45.580 --> 00:37:47.894
But the storm drains and
all the smaller rivers

00:37:47.894 --> 00:37:49.810
are likely going to see
more flooding upstream

00:37:49.810 --> 00:37:52.775
because of that.

00:37:52.775 --> 00:37:57.450
- Lisa [? Tripp-- ?]
what about the airport?

00:37:57.450 --> 00:38:00.380
I notice it's close to
what you put on your map

00:38:00.380 --> 00:38:02.880
but doesn't involve it.

00:38:02.880 --> 00:38:05.950
Is it somehow immune from--

00:38:05.950 --> 00:38:06.890
- No.

00:38:06.890 --> 00:38:08.770
No.

00:38:08.770 --> 00:38:10.070
- -- all these floods?

00:38:10.070 --> 00:38:11.200
- No, actually it's not.

00:38:11.200 --> 00:38:12.570
And that's a very good question.

00:38:12.570 --> 00:38:15.860
So the maps that I showed
you were made for Mass DOT,

00:38:15.860 --> 00:38:17.840
so we basically
masked out anything

00:38:17.840 --> 00:38:20.190
that was outside of
Mass DOT infrastructure.

00:38:20.190 --> 00:38:24.030
But Massport asked that
question a long time ago,

00:38:24.030 --> 00:38:25.240
what about the airport?

00:38:25.240 --> 00:38:28.140
So actually, they've
used a lot of the output

00:38:28.140 --> 00:38:30.995
from the model that
was built for Mass DOT.

00:38:30.995 --> 00:38:33.620
And one of the things that Mass
DOT right from the beginning is

00:38:33.620 --> 00:38:35.328
say, we're going to
make this information

00:38:35.328 --> 00:38:37.630
available to other agencies
and other communities that

00:38:37.630 --> 00:38:39.505
want to use it for
their own, because it's

00:38:39.505 --> 00:38:41.630
the best available information
right now that there

00:38:41.630 --> 00:38:43.450
is in the Boston area.

00:38:43.450 --> 00:38:46.270
And so Massport has actually
done their own vulnerability

00:38:46.270 --> 00:38:47.460
analysis already.

00:38:47.460 --> 00:38:51.900
And that's why they bought
the temporary flood barriers,

00:38:51.900 --> 00:38:56.250
because they now have a really
good idea of-- interestingly,

00:38:56.250 --> 00:39:00.290
it's not until about 2070
that the actual airport itself

00:39:00.290 --> 00:39:00.890
is impacted.

00:39:00.890 --> 00:39:02.566
It's fairly high up.

00:39:02.566 --> 00:39:04.190
It doesn't look at
when you're landing,

00:39:04.190 --> 00:39:08.080
but it's actually fairly
high up above the high tide.

00:39:08.080 --> 00:39:10.880
But they do have vulnerability
and they actually

00:39:10.880 --> 00:39:12.870
have a resiliency
officer, now, who

00:39:12.870 --> 00:39:14.924
has implemented a
lot of strategies

00:39:14.924 --> 00:39:15.840
for dealing with that.

00:39:15.840 --> 00:39:19.070
Because the airport is
an important recovery

00:39:19.070 --> 00:39:24.030
and evacuation component as
well as normal transportation.

